.TH _PRINTF 3 "March 2026" "Holbertonschool" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- print formatted output to standard output
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.PP
.nf
int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function writes to the standard output (stdout) under control of
.IR format ,
a string that contains ordinary characters and conversion specifiers
introduced by
.BR % .
.PP
This implementation supports a subset of the specifiers described in
.BR printf (3).
It does not implement flag characters, field width, precision, length
modifiers, or the C library\(cqs printf buffering.
.PP
Supported conversion specifiers:
.TP
.B %c
Print a single character from the corresponding
.B int
argument.
.TP
.B %s
Print the string pointed to by the corresponding
.B "char *"
argument. If the pointer is NULL, the characters
.B (null)
are printed.
.TP
.B %%
Print a literal
.BR % .
No argument is consumed.
.TP
.B %d,\ %i
Print the signed decimal representation of the corresponding
.B int
argument.
.PP
If
.I format
contains
.B %
with no following character (end of string),
.B _printf()
returns \-1.
.PP
If
.B %
is followed by a character that is not one of the specifiers above,
a literal
.B %
and that character are printed (two characters). No argument is read
for that conversion.
.SH RETURN VALUE
On success,
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters printed (not counting string
terminating null bytes in memory).
.PP
If
.I format
is NULL, if writing to standard output fails, or if the format string
ends right after
.BR % ,
.B _printf()
returns \-1.
.SH EXAMPLES
.RS
.nf
#include "main.h"

_printf("Hello, world\\n");
_printf("Char: %c\\n", 'Z');
_printf("String: %s\\n", "Holberton");
_printf("Percent: %%\\n");
_printf("Int: %d\\n", 42);
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3),
.BR write (2),
.BR stdarg (3)
